<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,151,1472]" pageId="13" pageNumber="464">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,393,1303,1328]" pageId="13" pageNumber="464">Biological notes.</emphasis>
The specimens have been found in bamboo shoots, in cloud and rain forests, under a slab on pile of cut chips and bark, in floor litter on a slope above stream-good forest cover. Some specimens were collected by Berlese extraction of leaf litter.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="464" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,151,1472]" pageId="13" pageNumber="464">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1412,1437]" pageId="13" pageNumber="464">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name refers to the brown color of the entire body and it is a Latin masculine adjective: 
<taxonomicName box="[267,377,1449,1472]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Hypotelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="464" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="castaneus">
<emphasis box="[267,377,1449,1472]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="464">castaneus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(of the color of chestnuts).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
